---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'What to Do After Wage Theft | wagetheftcalc.com';
const description = 'Immediate steps to protect your rights and recover stolen wages after a wage theft violation.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>What to Do After Wage Theft</h1>
  <h2>Document Everything Now</h2>
  <p>Gather and preserve: all pay stubs, bank statements showing deposits, personal time logs (texts, calendar entries noting hours worked), offer letters, and any communications about hours or pay. Do this before leaving the job — access to records may be cut off.</p>
  <h2>Calculate Your Loss</h2>
  <p>Use our calculator to estimate unpaid wages. Track each week separately if your hours or pay rate varied. The more detailed your records, the stronger your claim.</p>
  <h2>Consider Whether to Report Internally</h2>
  <p>Raising the issue with HR or your employer is not required but can sometimes resolve errors quickly. Get any response in writing. Internal complaints are protected activity under the FLSA anti-retaliation provisions.</p>
  <h2>File a Claim</h2>
  <p>File with the DOL Wage and Hour Division (free, no attorney needed), your state labor commissioner, or hire an employment attorney for a private lawsuit. Most employment attorneys offer free consultations and handle these cases on contingency.</p>
  <h2>Watch for Retaliation</h2>
  <p>Document any adverse actions after you complain — termination, demotion, schedule reduction, or hostile treatment. Retaliation is a separate violation with additional remedies.</p>
</BaseLayout>
